<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-030-035 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 428 853</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Oct 22 1991 v5 n36 p6(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Future NetWare could be plug-in: Novell responds to Windows NT.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wylie, Margie.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Novell Inc is working on a version of its NetWare networkoperating system that will work with any operating system orkernel.andP;  Already, version 3.11 of NetWare can be modified to runon any platform.andP;  Possibly, NetWare could someday become a plug-inmodule that offers network services to several different operatingsystems, including the Macintosh operating system; MicrosoftWindows NT; and Taligent, the operating system kernel to bedeveloped by IBM and Apple.andP;  Novell's quickness in developingports to all available environments could result in its continueddominance of the market.andP;  Microsoft Corp intends to battle fordominance with Novell: its LAN Manager will be incorporated intoportable versions of Windows NT.andP;  The rapid success of Windowstechnology promises Microsoft a large user base for its networkingservices.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Novell Inc. (Product development).andO;Ticker:    NOVL.andO;Product:   NetWare (Network operating system) (Product development)Microsoft Windows NT (Operating system) (Computer programs).andO;Topic:     Product DevelopmentNetwork Operating SystemsSoftware MigrationCompatibilityOperating Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Next-generation networking. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Novell responds to Windows NTandM;By Margie WylieandM;Dallas -- The NetWare of the future will not be particular about whoseoperating system or kernel it works with, Novell Inc. said last week.andM;At a press conference held here at NetWorld '91, Darrell Miller, vicepresident of Novell, said that Version 3.11 of the company's networkingoperating system is identical to a separate product once called PortableNetWare.andP;  The result is that today's top-of-the-line NetWare can be adaptedto run on any platform, Miller said.andM;Someday that could mean that NetWare will become a plug-in module thatprovides network services to many different operating systems, including theMac OS (see related story, Page 1) or OS/2,  e hinted.andM;Novell will port NetWare to run on Microsoft's Windows NT kernel andTaligent, the OS kernel to be devised by the Apple/IBM Corp. joint venture ofthe same name, Miller said.andM;By porting NetWare to every available environment, Novell will continue todominate the network market, Miller claimed, even in the building-blockenvironment of the future.andM;Not surprisingly, Microsoft Corp. disagrees.andP;  The company plans to popularizeits LAN Manager networking services by incorporating them into the portableversion of its popular operating system, Windows NT.andP;  The company has shipped6 million copies of Windows, with 8 million expected by year-end, accordingto San Jose, Calif.-based Dataquest Inc.andM;Today, however, NetWare's portability means that when third parties adapt thesoftware to other platforms, such as Unix, VM/MVS and VMS, it retains thesame features, including AppleTalk services for Mac users.andM;But after years of diagrams that show network modules snapping neatly intoplace, Novell, Microsoft and Taligent should understand if their big plansfor the future of networking are met with some skepticism.andP;  &quot;It's all a verypleasant scheme, but making it work is another thing,&quot; said Peter Francis, ananalyst at Dataquest.andO;</TEXT></DOC>